                <h1 class="activity-page-title">Story Collection</h1>
                <h2 class="activity-page-question">Why do this?</h2>
                <p class="activity-page-question-answer">This quiz will test your understanding of local climate change
                    and urban forestry issues.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="col-md-9 right-panel-adjustment activity-page-right-panel-column-adjustment container-fluid">

            <div>
                    <h3 class="activity-heading-1 heading-color-adjustment">Assignment:</h3>
                    <p>Read Cookit background to answer questions 1-4. Walk around your block and search up answers online for questions 5 & 6.</p>
                    <p>The questions below are just examples - feel free to come up with your own that match the interests and issues in your own community.
                      Once complete, discuss the answers with the group. Hold a trivia quiz activity at someone’s home or a community event, and share answers.</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <button class="collapsible"><h4 class="heading-color-adjustment">1. What is B.C.’s 2050 carbon emissions reduction target?</h4></button>
              <div class="content">
                <p>70% below 2007 carbon emmison levels</p>
              </div>

              <button class="collapsible"><h4 class="heading-color-adjustment">2. What produces the most carbon emissions from households in B.C.?</h4></button>
              <div class="content">
                <p>Building heating</p>
              </div>

              <button class="collapsible"><h4 class="heading-color-adjustment">3. What is the average carbon footprint of residents in B.C.?</h4></button>
              <div class="content">
                <p>The average carbon footprint of residents in B.C is 10-14 tonne per person.</p>
              </div>

              <button class="collapsible"><h4 class="heading-color-adjustment">4. How many trees is Vancouver planning to plant from 2010 to 2020?</h4></button>
              <div class="content">
                <p>The municipal government has a stated goal of planting 150,000 new trees by 2020 to densify Vancouver’s so-called “urban forest canopy.”</p>
              </div>

              <button class="collapsible"><h4 class="heading-color-adjustment">5. What kind of tree provides the biggest canopy on your street?</h4></button>
              <div class="content">
                <p>Answers may differ</p>
              </div>

              <button class="collapsible"><h4 class="heading-color-adjustment">6. Are there any trees on your street that are native to your region?<br>
                If yes, what kind?</h4></button>
              <div class="content">
                <p>Some of the trees that are native to Costal BC are: Amabalis fir, Arbutus, Black Cottonwood, Douglas-fir, Mountain hemlock, Sitka spruce, Western hemlock, Western red-cedar.
                However, answers may differ depending on where you live.</p>
              </div>

        </div>

    </div>
